108: New Year's Day (Nyårsdagen) January 1. This is a public holiday in Sweden, marking the start of the new calendar year. It is a day for rest and often for recovering from New Year's Eve celebrations.
Twelfth Night (Trettondagsafton) January 5. While not a public holiday, many businesses close early on this day. It is the eve of Epiphany and marks the end of the Christmas season for many.
Epiphany (Trettondedag jul) January 6. This is a public holiday in Sweden, commemorating the visit of the Magi to the Christ Child. It is often a quiet day for reflection.

Waffle Day (Våffeldagen) March 25. This is an unofficial observance where Swedes traditionally eat waffles, often with jam and whipped cream. It coincides with the Christian holiday of Annunciation (Vårfrudagen).

Shrove Tuesday (Fettisdagen) This is an unofficial observance, a movable feast day occurring 47 days before Easter Sunday. It is famous for the consumption of "semla" buns, a traditional Swedish pastry filled with almond paste and whipped cream.

Good Friday (Långfredagen) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the Friday before Easter Sunday. It commemorates the crucifixion of Jesus Christ and is traditionally a solemn day.

Easter Sunday (Påskdagen) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the first Sunday after the first full moon on or after the vernal equinox. It celebrates the resurrection of Jesus Christ and is often marked by family gatherings and Easter eggs.
Easter Monday (Annandag påsk) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the Monday after Easter Sunday. It is another day for relaxation and family time following Easter Sunday.

Walpurgis Night (Valborgsmässoafton) April 30. This is an unofficial but widely celebrated observance. Swedes gather around bonfires, sing traditional songs, and welcome spring. It is not a day off work.
Labour Day / May Day (Första maj) May 1. This is a public holiday in Sweden, observed as International Workers' Day. It is often marked by political demonstrations and parades.

Ascension Day (Kristi himmelsfärdsdag) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring 39 days after Easter Sunday, always on a Thursday. It commemorates the ascension of Jesus Christ into heaven.
Mother's Day (Mors dag) Last Sunday in May. This is an unofficial observance where mothers are celebrated. It is not a public holiday.

National Day of Sweden (Sveriges nationaldag) June 6. This is a public holiday, celebrating the election of Gustav Vasa as king in 1523 and the adoption of a new constitution in 1809. It is marked by flag-raising ceremonies and public celebrations.

Midsummer's Eve (Midsommarafton) This is an unofficial but widely observed holiday, occurring on the Friday between June 19 and June 25. Many businesses close early or are completely closed. It is one of the most important celebrations in Sweden, marked by dancing around a maypole, flower wreaths, and traditional food.
Midsummer's Day (Midsommardagen) This is a public holiday, occurring on the Saturday after Midsummer's Eve. It is a day for relaxation after the previous day's festivities.

Crayfish Party Season (Kräftskivesäsong) This is an unofficial observance, typically taking place in August. Swedes gather for outdoor parties to eat crayfish, often with schnapps and singing. It is not a specific holiday but a cultural season.

Surströmming Premiere (Surströmmingspremiären) Third Thursday in August. This is an unofficial observance marking the release of the year's fermented herring. It is a niche but significant cultural event for some.
Cinnamon Bun Day (Kanelbullens dag) October 4. This is an unofficial observance dedicated to the popular Swedish pastry, the cinnamon bun. Bakeries and cafes often offer special deals.

All Saints' Day (Alla helgons dag) This is a public holiday, a movable feast day occurring on the first Saturday in November, between November 3 and November 9. It is a day to remember deceased loved ones, often by visiting graves and lighting candles.
Father's Day (Fars dag) Second Sunday in November. This is an unofficial observance where fathers are celebrated. It is not a public holiday.

Lucia (Luciadagen) December 13. This is an unofficial but very important cultural observance, especially in schools, churches, and workplaces. It involves processions with singing, candles, and traditional saffron buns (lussekatter). It is not a public holiday.

Christmas Eve (Julafton) December 24. This is an unofficial but widely observed holiday. Most Swedes celebrate Christmas on this day, with family gatherings, gift-giving, and a traditional "julbord" (Christmas buffet). Many businesses close early or are completely closed.
Christmas Day (Juldagen) December 25. This is a public holiday in Sweden, a quieter day for family and relaxation after the Christmas Eve celebrations.
Boxing Day / Saint Stephen's Day (Annandag jul) December 26. This is a public holiday in Sweden, often used for visiting relatives or engaging in post-Christmas sales.

New Year's Eve (Nyårsafton) December 31. This is an unofficial but widely observed holiday. Many businesses close early. It is celebrated with parties, fireworks, and often a traditional dinner to welcome the new year.

119: Alec Baldwin: Alexander Rae Baldwin 3rd, born on April 3, 1958, is an American actor, comedian, and producer. He is the eldest of the four Baldwin brothers, all of whom are actors. Alec Baldwin is widely recognized for his role as Jack Donaghy in the critically acclaimed television series "30 Rock," which earned him 3 Golden Globe Awards, 3 Screen Actors Guild Awards, and 2 Primetime Emmy Awards. His notable film performances include playing Jack Ryan in "The Hunt for Red October," Blake in "Glengarry Glen Ross," and Alan Hunley in "Mission: Impossible - Rogue Nation" and "Mission: Impossible - Fallout." He is also well-known for his recurring impersonation of Donald Trump on the sketch comedy show "Saturday Night Live," which garnered him another Primetime Emmy Award.

Daniel Baldwin: Daniel Leroy Baldwin, born on October 5, 1960, is an American actor, director, and producer. He is the second eldest of the Baldwin brothers. Daniel is perhaps best known for his role as Detective Beau Felton in the crime drama television series "Homicide: Life on the Street," which aired from 1993 to 1995. His film credits include "Vampires" (1998), where he played Anthony Montoya, and "Ned Blessing: The Story of My Life and Times" (1993), in which he portrayed the titular character. He has also appeared in numerous other films and television shows throughout his career.

William Baldwin: William Joseph Baldwin, born on February 21, 1963, is an American actor, producer, and writer. He is the third of the four Baldwin brothers. William gained prominence for his roles in films such as "Backdraft" (1991), where he starred as firefighter Brian McCaffrey alongside Kurt Russell and Robert De Niro. Other significant film appearances include "Flatliners" (1990) as Joe Hurley, "Sliver" (1993) as Zeke Hawkins, and "Fair Game" (1995) as Max Kirkpatrick. On television, he is known for his recurring role as Dr. William van der Woodsen in the popular series "Gossip Girl" and for his work on "Dirty Sexy Money."

Stephen Baldwin: Stephen Andrew Baldwin, born on May 12, 1966, is an American actor, director, producer, and author. He is the youngest of the four Baldwin brothers. Stephen is widely recognized for his role as Michael McManus in the critically acclaimed 1995 film "The Usual Suspects." His other notable film appearances include "Bio-Dome" (1996) as Bud Macintosh, "The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas" (2000) where he played Barney Rubble, and "Threesome" (1994). In addition to his acting career, Stephen Baldwin is also known for his outspoken Christian faith and has participated in various reality television shows.

130: Launch Complex 39A: Located at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, this historic launch pad was originally constructed for the Apollo program's Saturn 5 rocket, which carried astronauts to the Moon. Following the Apollo program, it was extensively modified and became a primary launch site for the Space Shuttle program, hosting numerous missions including the deployment of the Hubble Space Telescope and the construction of the International Space Station. After the Space Shuttle's retirement, it was leased to SpaceX, which has since used it for launches of its Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy rockets, including missions for NASA.

Launch Complex 39B: Also located at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, Launch Complex 39B served as a launch site for the Apollo program's Saturn 5 rockets and later for the Space Shuttle program. It was the launch site for Apollo 10 and several Space Shuttle missions. After the Space Shuttle program, it was reconfigured to support NASA's Space Launch System, the powerful rocket designed for the Artemis missions to the Moon and eventually Mars. It is currently active and used for these deep-space exploration missions.

Launch Complex 39C: A smaller, conceptual launch pad located at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, adjacent to Launch Complex 39B. It was originally planned as a third Saturn 5 launch pad for the Apollo program but was never fully constructed or utilized for that purpose. More recently, it has been developed as a small-class launch pad, primarily used for testing and potential future small launch vehicles, though it has not hosted major operational NASA missions in the same vein as 39A and 39B.

Space Launch Complex 5: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this pad is famous for hosting the first American human spaceflight, Alan Shepard's Mercury-Redstone 3 mission in 1961. It was primarily used for the Mercury-Redstone suborbital flights and later for some Redstone rocket test flights.

Space Launch Complex 14: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this pad was a key site for the Mercury program, launching all four orbital Mercury missions, including John Glenn's historic Friendship 7 flight, the first American to orbit the Earth. It was used for Atlas-D rockets carrying Mercury capsules.

Space Launch Complex 19: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this pad was exclusively used for the Gemini program, launching all 10 crewed Gemini missions between 1965 and 1966. It launched Titan 2 rockets with Gemini spacecraft.

Space Launch Complex 17: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this complex consisted of two pads, 17A and 17B. It was extensively used for Delta rockets, which launched numerous NASA scientific and communication satellites, including Mars Pathfinder and the Mars Exploration Rovers Spirit and Opportunity. It was active for many decades before being decommissioned.

Space Launch Complex 36: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this complex also had two pads, 36A and 36B. It was primarily used for Atlas-Centaur rockets, which launched many significant NASA missions, including the Pioneer and Surveyor lunar probes, and later Mars Observer and Cassini-Huygens. It was active for over 40 years.

Space Launch Complex 37: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this complex had two pads, 37A and 37B. Pad 37B was used for the Saturn 1B rocket, which launched the first crewed Apollo mission, Apollo 7, and later Skylab missions. After a period of inactivity, it was reactivated and modified for the Delta 4 Heavy rocket, which has launched several NASA payloads, including the Orion Exploration Flight Test 1.

Space Launch Complex 40: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this pad was originally used for Titan 3 and Titan 4 rockets, launching various military and NASA payloads. After its Titan operations ceased, it was leased to SpaceX and extensively reconfigured for their Falcon 9 rocket. It is now a primary launch site for SpaceX, launching numerous commercial and NASA-contracted missions, including resupply missions to the International Space Station.

Space Launch Complex 41: Located at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida, this pad was initially used for Titan 3 and Titan 4 rockets, including the launch of the Voyager probes for NASA. It was later reconfigured and is now exclusively used by United Launch Alliance for their Atlas 5 rocket. The Atlas 5 has launched a vast number of NASA science missions, including the Mars Science Laboratory (Curiosity rover), New Horizons, and the James Webb Space Telescope.

Space Launch Complex 2: Located at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California, this complex consisted of two pads, 2W and 2E. It was primarily used for Delta 2 rockets, which launched numerous NASA scientific missions into polar orbits, including the Mars Phoenix lander, the Gravity Recovery and Climate Experiment (GRACE), and the Kepler space telescope. It was decommissioned after its final Delta 2 launch.

Space Launch Complex 3: Located at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California, this complex had two pads, 3E and 3W. Pad 3E was used for Atlas and Titan rockets, and is now used by United Launch Alliance for Atlas 5 launches. Atlas 5 from Vandenberg has launched NASA missions requiring polar orbits, such as the Landsat series and the Joint Polar Satellite System. Pad 3W was used for Atlas and Titan rockets, including some NASA payloads.

Space Launch Complex 4: Located at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California, this complex had two pads, 4E and 4W. Pad 4E was used for Titan 4 rockets, and is now used by SpaceX for Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches. SpaceX launches NASA-contracted missions from here, particularly those requiring polar orbits. Pad 4W was also used for Titan rockets.
